The Module & FSView; for & konqueror; provides a further view of objects with the MIME-Type inode / directory with local files. it can be used as an alternative for the different symbol and text views to view the content of your local file system.
The peculiarity of & FSView; is to display nested folder hierarchies using a so-called tree map. tree-maps allow the representation of the size of objects in nested structures. each object is represented by a rectangle whose area is proportionally to its size. this size must have the property that the sum of the sizes of the child objects is smaller or equal to the size of the object.
With & FSView; the size is the size of a file or folder, whereby the size of a folder is defined as the sum of the size of the entries. in this way, large files, even then easily detected, can be easily detected when they are far down in the folder hierarchy. therefore, & FSView can be considered as a graphical and interactive version of the & UNIX command.
In & FSView; is an entry in the Treemap display a rectangle representing a file or folder in your filesystem.
The color of a rectangle that is switched over view color mode can be either depth for easy detection of the nesting depth or the representation of another file property, such as name, owner, group or MIME type.
A rectangle can be labeled with the different properties of the respective file or folder. for each property, you can specify whether it is displayed at all, only if there is enough space for displaying or whether the area of child rectangles should be used. furthermore, you can specify the relative position of the lettering in the rectangle.
In case of representation algorithms for Treemaps, the rule should be observed that the area is proportional to the size of the entry. at the Treemap in & FSView, this goal is not always maintained. frames are drawn to represent the nesting of entries. note that less space is lost for the frame if the rectangle is square.
How splitting the area of an entry for the subordinate entries takes place is left to the implementation. here it is for the caption and to avoid space losses through the frame always favourably dividing the areas in such a way that rectangles are created which are as square as possible. the best methods in this regard are rows, columns or recursive division.
You can set the minimum displayed space for an entry over the menu entry View Appendix to area. instead, a diamond pattern is drawn into the area of the parent item to indicate that this area is actually occupied by a subordinate entry.
Originally & FSView was conceived as a small test application and introduction to the use of the TreeMap widgets developed for the KCachegrind application.
