Modern digital cameras are characterized by the use of Compact & Flash, Memory cards and USB or FireWire (IEEE-1394 or i-Link) for data transmission. for the actual transfer to the computer, the camera is often used as a USB mass storage device. the connection can also be realized via the Picture Transfer Protocol (PTP) and its derivatives. older cameras may also use the serial port (RS-232).
& digitization; uses the program gPhoto2 for communication with digital camera. gPhoto2 also supports Picture Transfer Protocol, a widely used protocol developed by the International Imaging Industry Association. it allows the transfer of images from digital cameras to computers and other peripherals without the need for additional drivers.
Many old digital cameras use the serial interface for their communication with the computer. since photos are generally large files and transmissions over the serial port are slow, this connection is now deprecated. & digitised; supports these cameras and performs the transfer of images with gPhoto2. you will find a complete list of supported cameras under this link.
