The reason why you use a color-managed workflow is the colors that come from your camera or scanner a predictable deviation from the actual photographed or scanned colors. with a color-managed workflow, you can achieve that the colors on your monitor correspond to those of your camera or scanner and that match the colors you print or publish on the web to those from your digital darkroom.
If the theme comes to color management, everyone would like to know which buttons he has to press for the results he wants. unfortunately, color management means that you make informed decisions at every point of the image processing workflows. the purpose of this tutorial is to provide you with sufficient background information about color management. in addition, you should provide links with deeper information to make your own informed choices so that you can obtain the desired result.
If your picture workflow fulfils all six criteria specified below, you do not need to worry about color management.
You work on a monitor that is calibrated to the sRGB colour space. (see below for more information)
Your only other picture editions are by e-mail or the web, where sRGB is the de facto standard.
So if sRGB works so well and makes life so easy, why should you use another color space and have to worry about color manpower?
A visual example of the limitation of sRGB in comparison to the colors we can really see is presented below. it shows a 2-dimensional representation of all colors we can see, the horseshoe-shaped region, and the colors in sRGB colour space, the triangular region.
If you want to compare the 2-Dimensional representation of sRGB with some larger color spaces, visit Bruce Lindblooms's Excellent page and click Info and then on Information About RGB Working Spaces.
Do I have to uninstall my monitor if I chose to work only in sRGB colour space?
