& digitio; provides three different tools for sharpening. each of you has advantages in other areas.
Sharpening is a traditional tool for sharpening. it is very fast and easy, but produces grainy images, especially in dark areas.
Blurred mask works on the contrast of edges to make a picture sharper. actually, it does not sharpen bit, it works rather psychovisual. you can use it to atmospheric haze and it makes a really good job. the algorithm has been taken from Gimp and it is protected by copyright from Winston Chang.
Refocus is possibly the best of the three because it really improves the sharpness. it is a little more complicated in its application and has different parameters for customization.
Photos without focus as well as most digitized images need a correction of sharpness. this is because the digitizing process needs to merge colours with only minimal differences to one color point. this in turn results in sharp edges a little blurred. the same phenomenon can be observed when color points are printed on paper. SLR cameras typically require more after-sharpening than normal cameras for private users.
JPEG images often have a camera internal sharpness. images in the raw format, on the other hand, must always be sharpened during processing.
Some scanners apply a field of sharpness already during the image reading. if you disable them, you will get control of your image.
In some situations you can obtain useful results by sharpening a photo with the sharpening tool. you can go to the Correcting Door menu entry.
You should be careful with this, since the results do not work very naturally: the sharpness increases the sharpness of the edges, but also increases the noise. generally, the most useful technique for sharpening an image will refocus the tool. you will find further information and a comparison of all techniques for sharpening.
Sometimes you have the opposite problem: a picture is too crisp. the solution to draw the image a little soft is much easier than sharpening. use the tool to soften with the menu entry Correcting softness and experiment something with settings. the preview window on the right side of the dialog shows you the effect on your photo.
The filter Unsharp masking is a very good tool to remove sliders from your photos. a demonstration can be seen here.
The original image and preview help to edit the image. the preview window displays the output of the filter with the current settings.
There are two important parameters, the radius and the amount. the default values often produce good results and should be tried first. an increase in the radius or the amount amplify the effect. if you make the blurred mask too strong, noise and the impression of grenades are generated near sharp edges.
The radius determines how many pixels on each side of an edge are affected by the filter. high-resolution images allow larger radii. therefore, they should best sharpen images in their final resolution.
The amount represents the percentage between the original and the blurred image that is added to the original.
The threshold value is a fraction of the maximum RGB value and the applicable difference amount. thus, you can define a minimum difference thus for an edge of the filter. in this way areas with a soft switching between the tones are excluded from sharpen and therefore beauty errors in faces, skies and water surfaces are avoided.
