Here you can choose from different & graphviz; Layout algorithms. the entries, as described on the & graphviz website, are:
It produces hierarchical or layered graphs of directed graphs. the algorithm produces the edges in the same direction (from top to bottom or from left to right) and then tries to produce as short edges as possible and as few edge overlaps as possible.
The & neato; -algorithm is the standard for unwatered graphs. it produces representations according to the springboard model. the Kamada-Kawai algorithm is used, which is equivalent to statistical multi-dimensional scaling.
The & FDP; -algorithm produces a springboard layout for unwatered graphs. it uses the Fructman-pure gold heuristics, and includes a multi-point trigger for the treatment of large and clustered graphs.
The & Circo; -algorithm classifies the nodes in a circular manner according to the description of Six und Tollis, 1999, and Kauffman and Wiese, 2002. it is useful for certain diagrams of multiple cyclic structures.
