With this KIPI module you can import or convert your images stored in RAW to one of three JPEG, TIFF or PPM formats.
The conversion is based on the command-line tool dcraw from Dave Coffin. an original quote from Him is: do not expect dcraw to produce the same results as the software from your camera producer. sometimes you get better results with dcraw!.
First select the raw file to be converted and start the module. the Raw Image Converter window will then appear in the mode for a single image. with the button preview you can view the effect of your current settings on the image.
You can now adjust the values to optimize the conversion process. the first option determines whether the camera settings for the white balance are to be used. the essential parameters such as gamma, brightness and red / blue amplifier can be adjusted. if the result is not optimal, you can further process the image later.
A four-colour RGBG conversion can be selected so that you can use the contrast information. if your camera operates in RGB mode, the RGBG switch has no effect.
Once you are satisfied with the preview, you can choose one of the three output formats and save the conversion result. the filename remains the same and only the extension is adjusted accordingly. JPEG uses a lossy algorithm and produces the smallest file sizes for it.
The Tagged Image Format, TIFF, keeps all the information of your image and uses the lossless LZW compression.
If you plan to edit your images frequently or later use them elsewhere, you should not choose the JPEG format, as there is only a limited number of operations allowed before the image quality deteriorates. TIFF and PPM are better adapted to keep the original data.
If you choose JPEG as a storage format, the metadata that is contained in the RAW file is stored in the JPEG File in the Exif information.
If you have adjusted your settings, you can start the conversion with the Run button. if you want to cancel this process again, you can use Cancel.
Batch processing mode allows you to convert various images at one time. therefore, use this mode if you are certain, e.g. by testing on a single image, which is the best settings.
The available settings are almost identical to the version for single images. however, they have the possibility to overwrite existing file automatically. this is helpful if they were created in an earlier attempt. however, a preview is not available. the progress bar shows how far the conversion is advanced.
