A render mode corresponds to the entries in & Povray; s ini files. it determines the image size and quality of rendering. if you want to render a scene in different image sizes and quality levels, you can insert any number of render modes, from a quick preview to full images of the highest quality.
If you click on the render settings icon in the toolbar, or in the View Render menu, select the following dialog:
Each render mode has a name. you can enter any name, meaning it is a name that lets you recognize the properties of the mode.
In the map size you can enter the width and height of the rendered image. if you only want to render a small area of the image, select the check box subsection and enter the image section to render into the input fields.
In combination field quality you can select the properties that & Povray; used for rendering. this goes from a very simple color and light model to a model with complex-diffuse reflection light. a detailed description of the render properties can be found in the User's Guide to & Povray;.
If an image is rendered with just one beam per pixel, different errors can occur. these images often have a Moir pattern or step effects in curves and lines, and sometimes details are sometimes not displayed if they are smaller than a pixel in the representation. this effect is called aliasing.
& Povray; uses a technique called anti-aliasing to reduce the influence of these errors. generally, pictures with this property look better.
If you turn on anti-aliasing, calculates and connects & Povray; more than one ray per pixel. this technique is super-sampling.
& Povray; supports two methods of super-sampling. as standard is an adaptive, non-recursive method; adaptive because the super-sampling refers to the adjacent pixels. the second method is adaptive-recursively; recursively because each pixel is divided over and over again and adapted because the recursion depth depends on the calculated color values.
If you choose the first method, POV-Ray pursues a ray of pixels. if the difference between the color values to the adjacent pixel exceeds the given threshold, then both pixels are calculated by tracking a certain additional number of pixels with super-sampling. if you set the depth value to 4, a grid of 4 additional points is calculated, at a depth value of 5 then 5x5 (25) additional rays per pixel.
The difference between two pixels is calculated as follows: R 1, g 1 and b 1 are the values for red, green and blue of the first pixel, r 2, g 2 and b 2 are the values for red, green and blue of the second pixel. the difference is:
Diff = abs (r. 1 -r 2) + abs (g 1 -g 2) + abs (b 1 -b 2)
The recursive method starts with 4 beams per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the default threshold, then the pixel is split into 4 sub-pixels, which are monitored individually and evaluated for further subdivision. the maximum depth of the recursion can be adjusted with the depth value.
Another way to reduce the aliasing effect is the creation of noise for the beam process called Jittering. if you turn on Jittering, change & Povray; the rays around a tiny amount to avoid regular patterns.
The last setting for the quality of rendering is diffuse reflection. this is an experimental feature of & Povray; it takes a very long time to calculate a scene with this property.
On this card you can set whether the alpha channels are to be calculated by POV-Ray. a pixel is then transparent if the related rays didn't hit any object.
