Listening to music should be quite simple! for this reason, there is the setup wizard, which is displayed at the first start of & Amarok; if you want to upgrade your collection afterwards or simply do not like the wizard, then this quick start guide will help you. with your help you will have set up & Amarok; in a few minutes.
Creating a playlist is very simple. drag and drop items from the collection browser to the playlist. the small text field for filtering the collection facilitates you to search for certain pieces. if you are content with the playlist, you can save them with the help of the button playlist. you will find this button in the toolbar of the playlist window.
If you have your own playlists, you can add them to the playlist browser. if the playlist is included in the folders of your collection, and you have checked the option to import playlists, then these playlists are already in the tree view. with a right click on a playlist, you will find various ways to load the playlist.
To play an audio CD, select Actions Audio CD in the menu bar. it opens a file browser with several folders and the CD pieces in WAV format. simply drag the wav files to the playlist and then press the Play button.
The audio CD function uses the audio cd: / and is not compatible with all available drivers.
The burning function is also available in the playlist. just click with the right mouse button on an entry and follow the burning menu. you have here various ways to burn a CD.
& Amarok; requires the installation of some software packages. the required packages are listed below. additionally some additional packages are listed that make work with & Amarok; more pleasant.
If you install these packages via a package management system (e.g. RPM or apt), you must also install the development versions of these packages!
& Amarok; is a versatile multimedia player. it offers many different ways to keep your music collection under control. like any normal multimedia player also has & Amarok; a player window with the most important features. in addition, & Amarok; a playlist that is superior to all others.
This chapter explains how all the functions of & Amarok are used, including creating a collection and a playlist.
The Player Window is your one-click & Amarok; control center. at the top of the window there is a running text display that shows the currently running piece or the current stream. right below is the area, the playing time, bit rate and samplerate of the current play. a click on this area changes the display of the already expired playing time for the remaining time of the play.
In addition, the Player window contains a selection of audio analyzers, even under the runtime display. you can switch by the available Analyzer by clicking on the area with the left mouse button.
The & Amarok; Analyzer can be separated from the player window. press d on your keyboard and the current analyzer is displayed in an independent, enlarged window.
The PL and EQ buttons also contain the PL and EQ buttons. the PL button activates or deactivates the playlist window, while the EQ button is used to set up equalizers.
The rest of the player window consists of the playback buttons, the volume control and the piece-position slider. use the sliders to adjust the piece position or volume. with the playback buttons you can start / stop playback and switch to the next or previous piece.
The use of the built-in equalizer is simple and works with all audio operators. there are 17 presets, from classic to techno, and you can easily create your own presets.
To view the equalizer, use Tools Equalizer from the main menu or click the EQ button in the player window. once you select the check box Equalizer, the equalizer is in operation.
The & Amarok playlist; is the most advanced playlist of all available for & kde; available multimedia players. it has many features that do not exist in any other player. but don't let the abundance of functions deter you, they are all easy to use.
The playlist window can be divided into two main areas, on the left hand side is the navigation pane. in the navigation pane you will find some of the excellent functions of the playlist, such as the context browser. on the right-hand side is the playlist itself. the playlist is easy to use and yet even for advanced users Powerful enough.
The context-browser features three sub-windows: music, text and artist. these three sub-windows will later be explained in detail.
If you have used earlier versions of & Amarok; perhaps you may notice that the bottom window has dropped off. the information presented here has now been distributed to other parts of & Amarok; the information collected in the Statistics window can also be viewed (Extras Statistics).
The music subwindow displays information about the currently running piece, as well as the artist and the album.
The first section in this sub-window displays information about the piece. in the title there is the name of the piece, artist and the album. below you see the cover picture of the album and next to it a MusicBrainz symbol. click on this icon to see the piece in the MusicBrainz database.
Below the MusicBrainz symbol you will find more information about the current piece. you can see here how often and when the piece was played for the first and last time as well as its evaluation.
To show cover images in the context browser, the cover pictures need to be in the same folder as the current piece. the file formats .jpg, .jpeg, .gif and .png are supported. the context browser will also display covers that are either downloaded with the cover management or embedded in ID3v2 tags.
The next section, Recommended pieces, lists several recommended pieces. if you click on any of these pieces, it will play instantaneously.
Among the recommended pieces are the favourite pieces of this interpreter. this section shows the five highest rated pieces of the current interpreter.
You can set which information to be displayed in the music subwindow. click with the right mouse button somewhere in the sub-window and select from the context menu.
The last section, albums of the artist, lists all the albums of the current artist you have in your collection. when you click on an album, it will fold and you will see the content of the album.
You can click on all pieces in the single areas to start playing right away. you can also right click on it and then select one of the possibilities to add the play or album to the playlist from the context menu.
In the Text subwindow, the downloaded song text is displayed for the running piece. this function is very flexible and it is possible to download texts from other web pages using self-written scripts. as soon as you click on the text subwindow, & Amarok tries to download the text for the piece from the Internet. if no text script runs, you can choose which to start.
The Edit button allows you to edit the lyrics. the changed version will then be saved in & Amarok; s collection database. no running text script is required.
The Find button opens a search on google.com according to the lyrics for the running piece (in an external browser window).
Grouping Artist - grouped only the top layer, each piece is displayed directly below the performer. albums or genres are ignored.
Grouping Artist / Album - First of all the pieces are sorted according to performer and below it will be another distribution according to the respective album. if you want to see compilations or soundtrack albums, this is the best view of your collection - these albums are displayed at the beginning of the list under Various interpreters.
Group Interpret / Year - Album - Sort by artist and then after the year of the album in descending order (the latest first). if the year is unknown for an album, the default 0 - album name is used.
Group album - All albums of your collection are sorted alphabetically by each other. the artist is ignored.
Grouping genre / interpreter - your pieces will be sorted by genre and among them according to performer.
Grouping genre / interpreter / album - This setting works just like the above but is also sorted by album below the performer.
With the help of the remaining buttons, you can customize and combine grouping at will.
With the last button you can change the settings for the collection. note: & Amarok; will automatically collect your collection once you change something to the selected folders. if you own a lot of pieces, this might take a while.
There is a search filter directly under the toolbar. it behaves in the list view as well as in the tree view. notes about using this filter can be found in the section on the playlist in this manual.
Under the search filter there is a selection box, with which you can filter the most recently added pieces to your collection. you can choose between the last 24 hours up to one year. of course you can also select your entire collection, whereby the filter is switched off practically.
By clicking with the right mouse button on an entry in the collection browser you will get the following options.
Load - This empties the current playlist and inserts the selected pieces in the currently valid order in playback.
Append to Playlist - Adjust the selected pieces of the current playlist. double click on an entry to get the same effect.
Set pieces in queue - This function inserts the selected pieces into the queue. this will be played next.
Save as a playlist... - Save the selected pieces as a playlist. you will be asked for a name under which the list should be saved.
Transfer to media player - Add tracks to the queue for transfer to the media player. for more details, see the Media Player Browser section.
Burn all pieces of this interpreter / Burn to CD - Therefore the selected pieces are sent to K3b and burned either as data or audio CD. if K3b is not installed, this option is not displayed.
Edit metadata (for n pieces)... - Open the dialog for piece information and lets you change the tags for one or more pieces.
(n) Move files to the garbage bins... - Create a confirmation dialog. if you confirm this, the selected files will be deleted from your computer.
Mark the selected album as a compilation, whereupon it appears among different interpreters.
Highlight compilation-mark - Changes a compilation marked as a compilation album back into a normal album. after that, the album will no longer be shown in different interpreters but once again with the corresponding artist.
The playlist browser is easy to handle with many playlists. among other things, it also includes smart playlists.
The bottom part of the playlist browser includes the smart playlists. these use & Amarok; s built-in database to automatically create some useful playlists at runtime. the smart playlists consist of:
Never played: a playlist containing pieces in your collection that have never been played.
Even created smart playlists are possible. click Add Smart Playlist to open the dialog to create a new Smart Playlist, where you can enter all necessary criteria for your new playlist.
The Media Player subwindow is used for connecting & Amarok; with your portable media player (e.g. iPod). to use your iPod with & Amarok; for example, it must be included before starting & Amarok; in / mnt / ipod. if & Amarok; started, you will find the pieces on your iPod by interpreter sorted in the top list view of the Media Player browser.
To transfer pieces to your iPod, drag the desired tracks from the playlist and drop them onto the performer list. if you're done, click Apply. this will upload the pieces to your iPod. if the transfer is complete, finish & Amarok; and release the drive connection for your iPod.
Under the toolbar there is a search area that allows you to search for a file. the search is particularly useful in folders with very many files, because in the file list all the files that do not match your search criteria.
In the lower part of the file browser, there is an address bar with which you can fetch music from a given URL. for example, if you want to type tar: / home / mike / musik.tar.gz and press Enter, you can click music in the file musik.tar.gz. now you can drag and drop the music from there into the playlist.
When the playlist is longer than in the window space, the attachment of files can be difficult by simply dropping. in that case, holding down the Shift key may be helpful: this automatically inserts dropped files at the end of the list, and not at the mouse position.
You can change the order by simply dragging the entries with the mouse to the desired location and drop. as soon as you enter letters, only the pieces that contain the letters will be displayed. in order to reset the filter, press the back button until the text field is empty again.
When you enter delimited search terms, & Amarok will search for entries containing all search terms. for example, if you enter one two three, the search will find all entries containing one, two and three.
If you enter the search terms OR, search for entries containing either the one or the other search term. example: one OR two OR three. in this example all pieces contain one or two or three (or a combination thereof).
If you want to search for entries containing spaces, then switch the search term with goose feet: Mike Oldfield. this will look for entries containing Mike Oldfield, but not for entries like Mike J. Oldfield.
If you specify a specific search column, you can search for larger or smaller ones. for example: rating: > 50. This searches for pieces that have a higher score than 50.
If you want to search for a piece that does not contain a certain search term, set a minus sign before the search term: -some search for pieces that do not contain something.
You can combine these syntax variants with each other at will. example: Mike Oldfield OR scores: > 50 -comment: bathroom. this searches for all pieces that either contain Mike Oldfield, or have a higher score than 50 and do not include the commentary bathroom.
You can set the sequence of entries by pressing the Ctrl key, and then click the right mouse button in the desired order on the entries. the entries will then be marked with a number. the number corresponds to the order in which the pieces are played.
The toolbar of the playlist is located at the bottom of the window. it contains buttons for some functions of the playlist. at the left-hand side, you will find the Add button that you can add to the playlist.
The next step is to undo and restore buttons, so you can undo or restore changes to the playlist.
In the middle of the toolbar there is a unique, increased analyzer. the refresh rate can be adjusted with a click of the right mouse button on the Analyzer.
The last button in the toolbar is menu. it opens the same menu as that which you get displayed in the Player window over the right mouse button. above this menu you can set up & Amarok; 's configuration.
There are many more available buttons for the toolbar, for example playback control and volume control. you can set up the displayed buttons by clicking on Menu and Setting Up Toolbars.
The status bar gives you a quick overview of the useful information about the playlist. it displays the title of the current piece, the number of pieces and the total playing time of all pieces. furthermore, the status for random mode and retrieval, a slider for the playing position and the play time of the current piece is displayed. the status for random mode and retrieval can be changed simply by double clicking on the respective display area with the mouse.
You can also disable the status bar. you can disable the Status Bar option in the General Settings dialog.
The context menu can be reached by clicking with the right mouse button in the player window, or by clicking on the menu in the playlist. from this menu you can access the settings of & Amarok.
A click on this entry will open the visualization plugin window. there you can select the visualizations of & Amarok.
Behind this entry there is a submenu with links to this document and other information about & Amarok;.
The cover management is a useful tool for managing your cover pictures. you can start it by selecting actions cover management in the collection browser.
The cover management includes a list view of all albums in your collection. you can view all the albums of an artist in your collection by selecting the artist on the left.
With the View menu you can choose what should be displayed in the cover management. select from:
After you set a piece to the queue, a number next to the title appears in the playlist. this number represents the order in which & Amarok; the pieces will play: 1 is played first, 2 as second, and so on.
If you want to add a piece to the queue, select the piece in the playlist and then click +. you can also easily add the pieces to the mouse or use the context menu in the playlist. you can then change the order of the pieces in the queue administration.
There are three types of dynamic playlists, two of which are already pre-given (details about setting up these will follow later).
Fills your playlist with random pieces from your entire collection and adds more random pieces while playing.
Adds pieces based on load .fm recommendations (previously: audio datagram). this mode requires that some pieces are already in your playlist. you don't need a .fm profile to work this dynamic playlist.
Double-click the desired playlist, drag it to the playlist window, or right-click on you and then select Load. this way your current playlist will be replaced by the new one.
The two pre-set modes of Random Mix and Playlist Mix immediately populate your playlist and you can add at least one piece from your collection. the pieces are added to the next piece change, so your playlist is only filled at the end of the first piece.
If you want to keep the current playlist, enable the last possible dynamic mode: settings Dynamic mode. this will use your existing playlist as a starting point.
The new button replenishes the current playlist and adds new pieces to the dynamic mode. editing Playlist opens the dialog to edit the playlist and you can change the appropriate settings.
With a right click on a dynamic playlist, you have the option to click Edit. then the dialog opens to edit the settings of the playlist.
Enter any name for the playlist here. however, the name should be unique to avoid confusion.
If this setting is not active, your playlist will continue to grow, the setting for upcoming pieces will be skipped and you will not hear a piece twice in this playlist. however, if the setting is active, the already played pieces will be removed in consideration of the settings.
Played pieces - this is the number of played pieces to be stored at the beginning of the playlist. this allows you to easily see which pieces have been played recently.
This is the number of pieces to be added to the playlist after each played piece. if you set more than 1 here, the playlist will continue to grow because only one piece can be played and removed each time.
