This chapter describes sound quality, encoders and compression ratios and helps you choose the right encoder.
If no audio information is to be lost, a lossless audio format is needed. besides FLAC there are also others like 'shorten' or 'monkey' that may be available for this distribution. drawbacks are the low compression ratios and hardly available commercial devices that can play these files.
Among the audio formats that lose information by data compression depending on their psychoacoustical model, MP3 and OGG are the most common. OGG today may have a slight advantage over MP3 in audio quality at lower bitrates (up to 128 kbps), but above this bit rate the differences become less important since both encoders generate very good audio quality.
O'not so 'free, lame is nevertheless provided with most distributions for free, but there are open license issues
+ High to very high sound quality (high bit rates), but slightly lower quality compared to OGG.
OGG - if only music is to be listened to from a computer or computer based music system and / or if one of the few existing OGG playdevices exist.
MP3 - when music is also to be heard on other devices, such as standard DVD players, portable devices (USB stick, memory card, hard drive) or special auto stereo systems. today - at the beginning of 2009 - these devices usually only support the MP3 format.
A short list of audio quality parameters and computed compression rates for 'lame' (MP3s) (see 'lame --help' for more parameters):
'--preset medium '= This setting results in good transparency for most people and most of the music
'--preset standard '= This setting should usually offer acceptable transparency for most people and most music pieces, and has quite high quality. good enough for hi-fi stereo systems.
'--preset extreme '= 224 up to 256 kbps VBR, compression ratio to 6.3. needs up to 320 kbps for complex pieces of music and less for less complex parts of the piece. good enough for hi-fi stereo systems with high quality. this is the preferred choice.
'--preset extreme -b 256 '= 256 kbps CBR, compression rate about 5.5. needs always 256 kbps for complex and less complex pieces of a song. some older devices need CBRs. good enough for hi-fi stereo systems.
'-h '= 128 kbps CBR common stereo, compression rate app. 11. 128 kbps for all pieces of a song. good enough for music of young people, portable devices and autoosteroners. but not good enough for better HiFi stereo systems.
'--preset Insane '= 320kbps CBR. this setting will be overdone for most people and most environments, but if you absolutely want the highest quality regardless of file size, then select this setting.
