Please note that the left side of the equality label is ignored. it is assumed that the GM patches are available in the correct order (from 0 to 127), so you may not change the order and leave no line for one of the 128 instruments.
For example, if your keyboard does not support a gun (GM-Patch 127), you can use a drum (e.g. with sound 60) that sounds similar to a gun. to do this, enter the following in the PATCHMAP section:
So if a MIDI file is to play a note with Patch 127 (gun shot), it takes Patch 100 (the drum on your keyboard) and plays the sound 60, regardless of which sound is in the MIDI file.
Please note that with the term drum patch the patch is meant, in which each note represents another percussion instrument (drum, cymbal, Maracas & etc;) and not the one where the sound is the pitch of the always same drum (like some keyboards own).
The keymap section is used to specify how sounds are mapped on a particular channel or instrument. the use is:
As with the PATCHMAP section, the sequence of lines is very important, as is their presence. therefore, you have to create 128 entries.
You can define multiple key maps for each channel and each instrument. you only have to use different names in the first line.
Keyboards are mainly used to map notes on the percussions channel. see for example the included keyboards.
This section can be used to map some channels to others. for example, if you want to swap the first and second channel, just make it in the CHANNELMAP section.
However, these settings are more useful for keyboards that have the percussion on a certain channel (General MIDI on Channel 10, others need channels 16 or 9).
MIDI devices need 16 channels, the CHANNELMAP section has 16 lines, numbered from 0 to 15, built according to the following pattern:
N is the channel that is mapped to the channel N. if you use the Keymap option, the key map with the name Name for this channel is needed. the corresponding keymap must of course continue to be defined forward in the file. if you use the ForcePatch option, all events will be ignored which will change the patch on that channel. in this case patch x will always be used.
The ForcePatch option can, for example, be useful to always use the percussions-patch on the percussion channel.
The value for PitchBenderRatio displays, in which ratio Pitch Bender events are multiplied. if a MIDI file sends a pitch Bender event with the value n, this is converted to the formula n * (r / 4096) and then relayed. the value 4096 is used to avoid decimal commas in the map file.
This setting is needed because GM pretends that a keyboard, which gets a pitch Bender event with the value 4096, should play a sound higher. unfortunately, some keyboards try to play two tones up to an octave higher. to find the right value on your keyboard, you have to try a bit with & kmid.
