There are many graphical tools to compare. why so & kdiff3;? let me briefly explain why I wrote.
The merge was very complicated, because one of the contributors made many changes while at the same time corrected the indentation in many places. another programmer had changed a lot of text in the same file.
The program I used showed me only the changed lines, but I couldn't see what had changed within these lines. and there was no indication of the places where only the indentation had changed. merging these changes was a small nightmare.
This was the beginning. the first version of & kdiff3; could display differences within a line and changes to white characters. later, a lot of other useful functions were added.
For example, if you want to compare text quickly, simply copy it to the clipboard and paste it into one of the comparison windows.
A function that made a lot of work was the comparing and merging of folders. this function converted & kdiff3; almost into a full-fledged file browser.
This is useful when two people work independently of each other on a piece of code and make changes. the original file (base) helps & kdiff3; when selecting the correct changes each. the merge-editor among differences windows enables resolving conflicts and simultaneously displays the expected result. in this editor you can even edit the result directly. the screenshot shows three source files when merging:
& K diff3; also helps to compare and merge the complete folders. this screenshot shows & kdiff3; when merge-merge:
& kdiff3; shows the exact differences and is based on the possibilities of today's color monitors. if you frequently have to check code, you will like this function.
Differences in white characters and tabs are displayed visible. if lines only differ in a certain number of white characters, one can see this at a glance at the summary in the column at the left side. (no more trouble if somebody changes the indentation.)
If a file is equal, and the other is different in one line, then the color indicates which file is different. red color means both files differ.
If all files have the same name but are in different folders, then you can make the typing work easier by just writing the file name of the first file completely. example:
Kdiff3 folder 1 folder 2 kdiff3 folder 1 folder 2 -o target folder kdiff3 folder 1 folder 2 folder 2 folder 2 folder 3 folder 3 -o target folder
The opening dialog allows for manual typing of file names, selecting a file browser (file...) or selecting a recently opened file from the drop-down list. the opening dialog remembers your selection and displays them next time. you don't need to specify a third file; if you leave the entry for C empty, the analysis of differences with two files is performed.
Using the Folder button... you can also select a folder. if you choose a folder, the matching or merging of folders is started. however, if a file is selected for A, B and C then use a folder, then use & kdiff3; the file name from A in the other two folders.
If merging is enabled, the input field is active for the target and can be edited. however, it is not necessary to specify an output file immediately. you can do this step later when you save it.
The set-up button opens a dialog with settings. here you can set options before starting the comparisons / merging.
Sometimes you don't want to compare a whole file but only parts of a text. & kdiff3; allows you to drag text parts from the clipboard into the active comparison window. the comparison starts immediately. in the opening dialog you do not need to select files, you can close the dialog with the Cancel button.
You can also drag and drop: just drag a file from a file manager or selected text from an editor and let it fall over a comparison window.
Sometimes a file contains, for example, several similar features. if you want to find out how similar these functions are, this would be a relatively big effort. you'd have to create two corresponding files, load them into & kdiff3; download and then compare them. now you can simply copy, paste and then compare the relevant sections.
Note: currently you can't remove anything & # diff3; only dropping text into a comparison window will be supported.
Warning: some editors interpret the drag and drop of text into another program than cut and paste (instead of copy and paste). in such a case, your original data could be lost.
The info line of the source window contains the characters A, B or C, the filename and the line number of the first visible line in the window. (note that window C is optional.) Each info line has a different color. (if the path to a file is too long, let the mouse rest for a while over the line.
The three source windows are assigned the letters A, B and C. a has the color blue, B the color green and C is magenta. (these presets can be changed via the Settings menu.)
When a difference is detected, one sees the color which file is different. if both files differ, the default color is red. (color for conflicts in the settings). the color scheme is particularly useful if you compare three files. that is good to see in the next section (merging).
When differences are found, the column shows the corresponding color. when differences in white characters are not so important, it is useful to see only the relevant changes. (C / C + +, for example, white characters are only relevant in strings and comments, for the preprocessor and in a few rare individual cases.)
The vertical line that divides the summary column from the text is interrupted at the places where the respective source file has no rows. if the line break is enabled, the line is displayed on broken lines.
The result window (under the comparison window) also has an info line with the title Output:, the filename and [encoder] if you have processed the result. usually it contains text by automatic merging, but often it also contains conflicts.
!!! until all conflicts are resolved the Save is deactivated!!! (use the buttons to find the next solved / unresolved conflict in order to find the remaining conflicts.)
If only two comparison windows are used, each difference is also a conflict that has to be solved manually.
By clicking with the left mouse button in the merge column in one of the windows, the group belonging to the line will be marked in all windows and the first row of the group will be displayed. (this will also cause a jump in the position in the windows, where the beginning of the group otherwise would not be visible.) This group will then be highlighted with the color background color for current pane and a black bar appears on the left.
Sometimes there is no more line left in the group due to automatic merging or manual editing; this is only a placeholder for the case that you change your mind and perhaps still select another source. this text does not appear in the final saved file, nor in a marker that you might copy and insert elsewhere.
The text & lt; merge conflict; however, appears in the clipboard if you copy such text from the result window. be careful with this function.
Note: when selecting the options for ignoring the options or activating Ignore C / C + + comments, changes in numbers or comments are also treated as white characters.
Navigate mainly with the scroll bars and the mouse, but you can also use the keyboard. if you click in one of the windows, you can use the arrow keys left, right, up, down, page descending, Start, End, Ctrl-start and Ctrl-End, Siw as you are used by other programs.
In the display window, you can also use the other buttons for editing. using the Insert button, you can switch between insert and overwrite mode. (default is insert mode.)
