The output of screen readers has the highest priority. it is preferred to all other orders and stops these jobs. if the output of the screen reader is read forward, the retained orders are resumed.
Warnings have the next priority. this level is important messages such as & eg; processor is subject to heat. a warning has priority and keeps the output of messages and normal text. these orders are resumed after the output of the warning.
News have the next highest priority. a message interrupts normal text. & kmouth; is an example of an application that uses messages. while you & eg; having a long text read on a web page, you can greet with & kmouth; someone who is just entering the room. & kde; notifications are also news.
The rest are simple text orders. every order that you send from the card order is a text order. KSayit is an example of a applications that uses text jobs. text orders are intended for the output of longer texts that do not have any particular urgency.
All four order types are processed in queues, with the exception of the output of screen readers. if an application sends the output of a screen reader, while & ktts; just one reads this, this output is stopped and stopped.
