This section cannot replace any further knowledge about IP networks. in this appendix only basic information about the integration of the PC is mediated in a small (home) network.
At the moment, IP networks are operated with TCP / IP version 4 (IPv4). IPv6 has never found widespread distribution. IPv6 is expected to be implemented in the near future. this description is therefore currently concentrated on the common IPv4.
One of the most important information is the knowledge of the IP address of a network interface. in other networks, on & eg, the network administrator is the contact point that assigns a valid IP address or, if available, DHCP can be used. in any case, the IP address cannot be chosen arbitrarily.
When setting up your own small (home) network, the IP address should be selected from a specific area reserved for this purpose in order to avoid IP address conflicts with the global (Internet) network.
Of course, access to the Internet can be made possible for such machines by setting a gateways.
For smaller networks, mostly addresses in the range from 192.168.1.1 to 192.168.1.254 are used. the area is large enough for networks up to 250 computers.
In addition, the netmask is usually set to 255.255.255.0, so that all computers are participants in the same subnet.
Some addresses are reserved for special things, 0.0eg; .0.0 and 127.0.0.1. the first is the so-called standard route, the second is the loopback address (localhost = your own computer). the default route is required for IP redirection.
The network address 127.0.0.1 is reserved for IP traffic in the local own machine. normally, the address 127.0.0.1 is assigned to a dedicated loopback interface, which works like a closed circle.
