& ksystemlog; is a & kde; Viewer for system logs. the program is suitable for inexperienced users who do not know where to get information about your system or where the system stores the various protocol files. furthermore, & ksystemlog; experienced users can quickly access information on problems that occur on their server.
& ksystemlog; helps users understand what makes your computer in the background. the task of & ksystemlog; is a simplified representation of protocol files of your own system. the program is suitable for inexperienced users who do not know where to get information about your system or where the system stores the different protocol files.
In addition, & ksystemlog; experienced users can provide quick access to information on problems that appear on their server. & ksystemlog; therefore, try to provide some advanced features to filter and evaluate the protocol files of certain programs.
In current version 0.4.1 has & ksystemlog; a number of useful features. this includes:
Support for many different types of protocol files, for the format of the Syslog server and for Samba
Many other functions are also included and are explained in the other chapters of this manual.
As you can see in the screenshot below, & ksystemlog; functions are available to easily filter and sort the single protocol lines of a protocol file. the individual options for sorting and filtering are shown in the next chapter of this manual.
After the start & ksystemlog; first try to open the main protocol file of the system - the system log. if this is not shown, and it opens instead of a small message box, so you have not started with system administrator privileges. under Linux, the protocol files are usually found in the / var / log folder, for which normal users usually have no permission to read.
You can also use the filter bar to filter by a selected criterion or by entered strings. the list of the log lines will now be automatically changed, so that only log lines will appear which match the selected filter. in the default setting, the list of logs will only be displayed if the filter search term is contained in one of the columns.
You can, of course, select another entry at this point, and the string of the filter search term will then only be compared to the entries in the corresponding column. for example, in the log file system log, select the process column, and then enter the name of a process in the filter bar, and then show you & ksystemlog; all protocol lines that have been sent or created by this process.
This option is enabled in the default setting and helps you to identify the important protocol lines. minutes lines of the level errors are displayed with a more conspicuous color as the step critic's protocol lines. the colored display of protocol lines can be switched off setup dialog.
If you want to display only certain processes (e.g. in the system log or in the Cron protocol), you can hide process identification (PID) in the process column. this can, for example, be useful if you want to examine the output of a particular command such as the start of the Samba server. in this case, use filter bar.
In addition, you can activate the To-New Lines option in the main window context menu to display all new incoming log lines.
& ksystemlog; allows to display multiple protocol files in separate sub-windows. to use this feature, use the entries in the menu window to open and manage additional sub-windows. once you have selected a subwindow, select a protocol to display in the menu.
