Welcome to the & kde; System V Init Editor, rather known (and so named) as & ksysv; This section introduces a few concepts and describes what you can do with & ksysv.
System V Init is rapidly becoming the standard for program start-up when running the system in the & Linux world. this is because it is easier to use, more powerful, and more flexible than traditional BSD init.
I will not go into historical aspects here (e.g. because I don't know about myself: -).
The init binary file is under / sbin and not under / etc. this is important because maybe someone could try to switch a machine to System V Init without reinstalling and reformatting. the & Linux; kernel first looks under / etc after an init file. therefore, you need to make sure that the old Init was removed from there if there was one.
The SysV Init also differs from the BSD init that the configuration files are in a subfolder of / etc instead of directly in / etc. this folder is called rc.d. .dat you will find rc.sysinit and the following other folders:
Init.d contains a lot of scripts. basically, you need a script for every system service you want to start when you boot the system or when you switch to another run level. system services include such things as network, NFS, & Sendmail;, httpd & etc; system services don't include such things like setserial, which is only started once. such calls are owned by rc.local.
Rc.local should be under / etc / rc.d if you need it. most systems have this file even if there is not much use for it. you can also put a rc.serial in / etc / rc.d if you want to do something with the serial port when you boot up.
