Some people want to have a simple way to set up machines for many purposes. I could & eg; a server runlevel that can only run httpd, & Sendmail;, Network & etc; I could also have a user runlevel, that & eg; & kdm;, Network & etc.
Here you will learn how to use & ksysv; it should not be very difficult because the program was designed as user-friendly as possible.
Using & ksysv; using a mouse or any other pointing device is simple to not say trivial: just drag an entry from the area of available system services to one of the six Runtime levels to start (or stop) at this level.
You can also move scripts between level n or change the position within a level by dragging it somewhere else. in doing so, the entry is removed from its original runlevel (or its position). this only happens if you pull an entry from the area of available system services.
Note: items are moved when you move them into a new area. to just copy them to a new runlevel, you must explicitly select Copy from the Edit menu or from the context menu and insert them into the target zone -- even if the same entry already exists in the target area of the action.
The sorting number of an entry can sometimes not be calculated. in such a case, you have to edit the sorting numbers of the surrounding entries before attempting to insert the system service again.
Note: currently there is no way to restore items thrown into the trash bin. so be careful.
You can use the Tab key to activate the different work areas (Available System Services, Runtime 1 Start, Runtime 1 Stop & etc;) as well as the cursor keys to make a selection above or below the previous ones.
To move an entry into another run level, move it into the clipboard with cut-out (you can also use Ctrl; X) and insert it into the desired level by inserting (using Ctrl; V).
To manually change the sorting number or the name of an entry manually, press the Enter key to open the Properties dialog. use the Tab key to switch between different fields. close the dialog by re-typing the input button to accept the changes, or press Esc to discard the changes.
Because of the risk of data loss, all entries in the File menu require confirmation before they are executed.
